SOFTWARE REQUIREMENTS
=========================================================================================================================
1.Operating System(Windows 10 or 11)
2.Browser(Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, etc...)
3.NodeJs(javascript runtime)--> https://nodejs.org/en/download/                 ||
4.MongoDB(database server)  --> https://www.mongodb.com/try/download/community  ||                             
5.Windows terminal (comes installed with windows 10 or 11)                        ||    NB: if you want to run it locally
6.Git(Source control)       --> https://git-scm.com/downloads                   ||                                                     
7.Heroku(Deployment)        --> https://www.heroku.com/                         ||

Hardware requirements
1.Minimum 8GB RAM
2.Minimum 50GB Available Disk space
3.Wifi Availability
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PROJECT TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS
=========================================================================================================================
* This project is web based application which uses the NodeJs framework.
* Follows an Model-Controller-Views(MVC) architecture.
* It has Authentication and Authorization routes and controllers to track users.
* It has web components in form of cards which shows the products and their prices.
* It has single pages of each product for ordering and also a litte details about the product.
* It has a cart section where you can confirm a purchase.
* Uses the twilio API to send users confirmation messages after a purchase.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

HOW TO SETUP LOCALLY
==========================================================================================================================
As mentioned earlier, this is a NodeJs application.The steps mentioned below should be followed accordingly.
The aim is to get the code from the git repository to run on the developer or reviewer's system.

Fetching git code to local system
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1.Change current working directory to Project directory.
--cd projectDirectory

2.Clone the repository from GitHub
--git clone https://github.com/Adu-P71/miniProject.git

3.Checkout to the development branch.
-- git checkout main

Installing dependecies
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1.Make sure npm is installed(It will be already installed if you properly installed NodeJs)
-- npm --version (the version of npm will be printed to the terminal if installed and an error if otherwise)

2.Install all dependecies(the package.json file contains the list of all dependecies used for this project)
-- npm install --save 

Running the application
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1.Set up all your environment variables in a ".env" file.

2.Start the app by running the start script.
--npm start

Deployment
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1.Create a heroku account.
-- https://signup.heroku.com/

2.Login to heroku
-- heroku login
  
3.Create an app on heroku which prepares Heroku to receive your source code.
-- heroku create

4.Deploy code 
-- git push heroku main

5.Now visit the app at the URL generated by its app name. As a handy shortcut, you can open the website as follows:
-- heroku open

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
END OF LOCAL SETUP 
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

If you just want to see how visit:
https://mini-project-app00.herokuapp.com

